Your fiction :

	"I recently upgraded to a 2842 VL, it is even better, and
	supported by most _major_ operating systems, except, for the Linux"

	"it seems that Adaptec will not release programming info to them"

	"As far as performance with a 486 motherboard, VL has a 
	_slight_ advantage in speed over a PCI, because PCI is a 
	bridge."

Reality : 

	A Linux driver for the 284x is available, via anonymous FTP
	ftp.cpsc.ucalgary.ca:/pub/systems/linux/aha274x.

	Adaptec has no qualms releasing documentation on the 
	hardware, although their tech support people don't
	allways know this.

	A blanket statement shouldn't be used concerning
	PC performance, as memory subsystem and other chipset
	features vary radically.  However, the buffering allowed
	by PCI, along with a larger proportion of i486 PCI 
	boards having 64 bit memory subsystems versus VLB 
	systems, usually give PCI a performance edge that 
	can be quite measurable (ie, two fold with S3 928
	boards on host->video transfers with many Saturn based
	i486-66 boards).

